---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AI Workflow Design: From Using Tools to Structuring Tasks — AI Agent Puzzle"
  description="Once you can use a tool, the next step is connecting several small steps so the AI can complete a more meaningful task. This page walks through the difference between a single tool and a workflow, the four basic ingredients, when to stop, the three workflow tiers, and how prompts shape the AI's path."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-workflow">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Tools Are Working — Now Have the AI Walk Through the Whole Task</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We already have a fairly stable MCP tool. It can take input, call an external API, handle errors, and return a clean response that both AI and humans can read. That's a good place to be. But in real work or study, <strong>we usually want more than a single small action</strong>.
        </p>
      </header>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">For example:</p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>Looking up the weather once <strong>isn't a complete workflow</strong></li>
        <li>Reading one article <strong>isn't a complete workflow</strong></li>
        <li>Creating one Notion page <strong>still might not be a complete workflow</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A useful AI workflow usually means <strong>chaining several small steps so the AI completes a more meaningful task</strong>. This page is about going from "single tool" to "AI workflow."
      </p>

      <!-- Section: tool vs workflow -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">A Single Tool Is a Button — A Workflow Is a Sequence</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Don't make "workflow" sound harder than it is. Think of a single tool as a button. The weather tool we built earlier:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Look up the current weather for a given city.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        It's simple: pass in a city, get back the weather. <strong>That's a single tool</strong>. But if we want the AI to help complete something closer to real life, there's more than one step. For example:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Based on today's Taipei weather, draft a short reminder suitable for class announcements.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">That involves at least:</p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Look up <strong>Taipei's weather</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Check whether the lookup <strong>succeeded</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Compose a reminder based on <strong>temperature and wind</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Use a <strong>tone appropriate for students</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text">If the lookup failed, <strong>don't make things up — explain why</strong></span></li>
      </ol>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">That looks more like a workflow.</p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          A single tool: "<strong>do one action</strong>."<br/>
          An AI workflow: "<strong>complete a task in order</strong>."
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: not free-running -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">A Workflow Isn't "Let the AI Run Loose" — It's Routing It</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        People hear "AI workflow" and assume <strong>"I just give the AI one sentence, and it figures out the rest."</strong> That's risky thinking. The AI is great at filling in blanks — but if it fills in too much, it starts guessing, mis-using tools, or doing things you never asked for.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So designing an AI workflow <strong>isn't about letting the AI do whatever it wants — it's about routing it</strong>. We can write the task like this:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        First, look up the current weather in Taipei.<br/>
        If the lookup succeeds, use the tool's response to compose three short reminders for students.<br/>
        If it fails, only state the failure reason and a suggested next step — don't guess the weather.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">That's already <strong>a simple workflow design</strong>. It tells the AI:</p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>What the first step is</li>
        <li>What to do on success</li>
        <li>What to do on failure</li>
        <li><strong>What it must not do</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        That's <strong>much more reliable</strong> than just "tell me if it's a good day to go out."
      </p>

      <!-- Section: 4 elements -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">A Simple Workflow Needs Four Things</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Don't make your first workflow complicated. Just nail four ingredients.
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Goal</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">What the workflow ultimately produces. e.g. <strong>a class reminder paragraph</strong>.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Source</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">What data the AI bases its decisions on. e.g. <strong>the weather MCP tool's response</strong>.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Order</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">What goes first, what goes next. e.g. <strong>look up first, then compose; not the other way around</strong>.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Format</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">What the final output looks like, e.g. <strong>"Reminder: 1. 2. 3." plus "Source"</strong>.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Once these four are in place,<br/>
          the workflow gets <strong>much clearer</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: build small first -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Don't Build a Mega-Workflow on Day One</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Once people learn the tools, they often want to build something huge:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Organize all my course material, generate handouts, create Notion pages, send student reminders, create quiz questions, and tally feedback.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        It's not impossible — just <strong>not a good first project</strong>. With many steps, one wrong turn somewhere derails everything after, and it's hard to tell which step broke.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Better to <strong>start small</strong> and grow:
      </p>

      <div class="flow-card flow-card--tall">
        <div class="flow-step">Look up data → Summarize</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ then evolve to</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">Look up → Summarize → Turn into a reminder</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓ then evolve to</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Look up → Summarize → Reminder → Notion draft</div>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Workflows should grow <strong>like Lego bricks, one block at a time</strong>.<br/>
          <strong>Don't try to build a tower from scratch.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Part 2: Prompt practice ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 2</span>
        <span class="part-text">Prompt Practice</span>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 1 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 1</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Turn the Weather Tool Into a Class-Reminder Helper</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We'll start with the weather tool from before. The original single tool was "look up the current weather for a given city." Now we wrap it as a small workflow: <strong>turn the lookup into a class reminder ready for posting</strong>.
      </p>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Prompt example</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the copyable prompt</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please use the weather-api tool to look up the current weather in Taipei.<br/><br/>
            Once it succeeds, organize the response into a short class reminder.<br/><br/>
            Follow these rules:<br/>
            1. Only summarize what the tool actually returned. Don't guess the weather.<br/>
            2. If the lookup failed, don't write a reminder — only state the failure reason and a suggestion.<br/>
            3. Use this fixed format:<br/>
            　Status:<br/>
            　Reminder:<br/>
            　Notes:
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        That prompt is longer than a one-liner, but much more stable. You're not just saying "write me a reminder" — you're telling the AI <strong>look up first, write second; how to handle success; how to stop on failure</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          That's <strong>the first step from a single tool to a workflow</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 2 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 2</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Lock the Output Into a Fixed Format</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For a workflow to stay stable, <strong>output format matters</strong>. If the AI replies differently every time, the next step is hard to chain on. Sometimes you'd get:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>Taipei is fine today, stay hydrated.</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">Sometimes:</p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>Based on the data, the temperature is 28°C and wind speed is 10 km/h, so students should...</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Sometimes a long paragraph. It's not unusable — but <strong>if you later route the result into Notion, an announcement, or another tool, this gets messy</strong>. So lock the format.
      </p>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Prompt example</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the copyable prompt</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please use the weather-api tool to look up the current weather in Taipei.<br/><br/>
            Once it succeeds, organize the response into a short class reminder.<br/><br/>
            Follow these rules:<br/>
            1. Only summarize what the tool actually returned. Don't guess the weather.<br/>
            2. If the lookup failed, don't write a reminder — only state the failure reason and a suggestion.<br/>
            3. Use this format:<br/><br/>
            　Status:<br/>
            　success or failed<br/><br/>
            　Data summary:<br/>
            　Two sentences summarizing the tool's response<br/><br/>
            　Reminder:<br/>
            　Three sentences students can read<br/><br/>
            　Needs human review:<br/>
            　Yes — this is data from an external API; the teacher should still verify before posting
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          One benefit of this format:<br/>
          <strong>humans can read it, and the AI can pipe it into the next step easily.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 3 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 3</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Add Human Review — Don't Let the AI Make the Final Call</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        At work, AI can speed things up — but <strong>that doesn't mean it should make every final decision for us</strong>. Especially for things touching students, classes, public announcements, grades, or personal data, keep a human checkpoint.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Add an important step to the workflow:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>Produce a draft — don't publish.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Prompt example</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the copyable prompt</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please use the weather-api tool to look up the current weather in Taipei.<br/><br/>
            Once it succeeds, draft a class reminder based on the tool's response.<br/><br/>
            Follow these rules:<br/>
            1. Only summarize what the tool actually returned. Don't guess the weather.<br/>
            2. If the lookup failed, don't write a reminder — only state the failure reason and a suggestion.<br/>
            3. Use this format:<br/><br/>
            　Status:<br/>
            　success or failed<br/><br/>
            　Data summary:<br/>
            　Two sentences summarizing the tool's response<br/><br/>
            　Reminder:<br/>
            　Three sentences students can read<br/><br/>
            Notes:<br/>
            1. Draft only.<br/>
            2. Don't publish on my behalf.<br/>
            3. At the end, list what the teacher needs to confirm.
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Now the AI behaves more like a <strong>TA</strong>. It can organize, draft, and check — but the publish decision stays with the human. We're not handing off judgment; we're <strong>handing off the repetitive, tedious organizing work</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Part 3: Safety + design ============ -->

      <!-- Section: stop conditions -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Workflows Need "When to Stop" Conditions</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A good workflow <strong>doesn't always plow through to the end</strong>. Some situations should trigger a stop:
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>The tool <strong>lookup failed</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Insufficient data</strong></li>
        <li>The user didn't provide required information</li>
        <li>The AI <strong>isn't sure which tool to use</strong></li>
        <li>The task involves <strong>delete, publish, send mail, change grades</strong> — high-risk actions</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In those cases, the AI shouldn't guess or decide on its own. Better:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        If data is insufficient, stop and tell me what's missing.<br/>
        If a tool returns failure, don't fill in the answer yourself.<br/>
        If a change or publish is needed, draft it and wait for my confirmation.
      </blockquote>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          These few sentences are simple but important.<br/>
          They make the workflow <strong>safer, and closer to how real-world work actually flows</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: 3 layers -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Workflows Come in Three Tiers</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For a beginner, think of three tiers.
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Organize</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Read → Summarize → Bullet points.</strong> Best for beginners; usually doesn't change data, so risk is low.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Draft</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Look up → Organize → Produce a draft announcement.</strong> Generates new content but doesn't publish; great for class material, reports, admin text, interview notes.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Action</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Look up → Create Notion page → Update field.</strong> Writes or modifies data — handle with care.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Practice in this order. <strong>Don't let the AI modify data on day one.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Example: a reading-notes assistant workflow</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Suppose we want to design a "<strong>reading-notes assistant</strong>." Its job isn't to write the report for the user — it's to <strong>turn an article into usable notes</strong>.
          </p>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Goal</h4>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">Turn an article into reading notes.</p>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Steps</h4>
          <ol class="numbered-list">
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Read the <strong>article content</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Identify the article's <strong>main question</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Pull out <strong>3 to 5 key points</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Capture the author's <strong>main argument</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text">List <strong>follow-up questions for further thinking</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">6</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Remind students that <strong>this is a draft</strong> — they still need to judge and add to it</span></li>
          </ol>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Output format</h4>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>Article topic:
Main question:
Key points:
Author's argument:
Follow-up questions:
What needs human review:</code></pre>

          <div class="highlight-card">
            <p class="highlight-text">
              It doesn't just hand back an answer —<br/>
              it <strong>shows the user the process of organizing the material</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Example: an interview-notes assistant workflow</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            For <strong>qualitative research, interview analysis, or social-issue work</strong>, you can design an interview-notes workflow.
          </p>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Goal</h4>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">Turn an interview transcript into <strong>preliminary thematic categories</strong>.</p>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Steps</h4>
          <ol class="numbered-list">
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Read the <strong>transcript</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><strong>Don't rewrite the interviewee's intent</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Identify <strong>recurring themes</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Add a <strong>short note for each theme</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text">If quoting, <strong>quote only short fragments and remind the user to verify against the original</strong></span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">6</span><span class="numbered-list__text">List <strong>spots that may need researcher judgment</strong></span></li>
          </ol>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Output format</h4>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>Preliminary theme:
Theme description:
Related quotes (summary):
What needs human review:
Suggested next steps:</code></pre>

          <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
            <p class="callout-text">
              This example is good at reminding the user: <strong>AI can help organize, but it can't replace researcher judgment</strong>. Interview data often involves context, emotion, background, and ethics — final calls stay with humans.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Section: design checklist -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">A Quick Checklist for Designing Workflows</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Before designing an AI workflow, ask yourself:
      </p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">What is this workflow <strong>ultimately producing</strong>?</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">What <strong>data does the AI need</strong>?</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Which steps go <strong>first</strong>, which go <strong>later</strong>?</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Which step <strong>uses an MCP tool</strong>?</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Which step is <strong>just text shaping</strong> with no tool needed?</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">6</span><span class="numbered-list__text">When should the workflow <strong>stop</strong>?</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">7</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Which results need <strong>human review</strong>?</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">8</span><span class="numbered-list__text">What does the <strong>final output format</strong> look like?</span></li>
      </ol>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          If you can answer all of these, the workflow is usually clear.<br/>
          If you can't, <strong>the task is probably still too vague to hand off</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: don't make a mega-tool -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Don't Wrap Everything Into One Mega-Tool</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Some people think: since I want a workflow, why not build one giant MCP tool that does it all? Like:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block code-block--bad" is:raw><code class="lang-python">do_everything()</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        It looks easy — but it's <strong>dangerous, because the bigger the tool, the harder it is to tell where things broke</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Better: <strong>keep tools small and design the flow carefully</strong>.
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><strong>Looking up data</strong> is a tool</li>
        <li><strong>Creating a page</strong> is a tool</li>
        <li><strong>Updating status</strong> is a tool</li>
        <li><strong>Text shaping</strong> can stay in the AI prompt — not every step needs to be a tool</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Smaller tools are easier to test. Clearer flows are easier to control. That's the principle from earlier pages: <strong>not "let the AI do everything," but "give it a clear scope and walk it through, step by step"</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: takeaway -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The Big Takeaway</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Going from a single tool to an AI workflow, <strong>the point isn't more tools — it's a clearer task flow</strong>. A single tool does one action; a workflow chains several actions in order.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Some early-design principles to keep:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Start with <strong>small flows</strong>, not big systems</li>
        <li><strong>Read, organize, draft</strong> first — writes and updates later</li>
        <li>Keep tools <strong>small</strong> and flows <strong>clear</strong></li>
        <li>On success, know <strong>the next step</strong></li>
        <li>On failure, know <strong>how to stop</strong></li>
        <li>Big decisions stay with <strong>humans</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-card highlight-card--final">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          The real value of an AI workflow isn't letting AI run wild.<br/>
          It's letting <strong>humans decompose the task</strong>, then letting AI<br/>
          do the <strong>repetitive parts faster and more reliably, inside a safe and reviewable scope</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .ai-agent-workflow {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

